As to the purpose of the poem I have tried to help the reader in judging for himself byn «amful division of the Argument. It will be seen that the rules are miscellaneous and have little or no method, and that the history of Poetry which Horace gives is more fanciful than real. It is impossible to look upon it as a finished poem. We are carried from precept to history, and from one sort of poetry to another without warning ; and though a general connexion may be traced between the principles of one kind and those of another, no pains are taken to separate the rules that belougto each. The rulee and history of the Drama are chiefly dwelt upon, with what particular bearing upon Roman poetry it is not easy to see. Much that is said can have no refer- enee to it at all, and could afford no instruction to a Roman.
